	<p>
		One challenge in chemistry is being able to draw 3-dimensional objects on a 2-dimensional sheet of paper. To aid in this, we often use wedges and dashes to represent bonds that not in the plane of the paper. Wedges are meant to represent bonds that are pointed toward the viewer. Dashes are meant to represent bonds that are pointed away from the viewer. So a tetrahedral shape for methane can be represented as shown below:
